The Simple Broker is Spring's built-in in-memory message broker.

The easiest way to think about it is:

It is a small post office inside your Spring Boot application.

Its job is simple:

Remember who subscribed to which destination.
Deliver messages to those subscribers.

It does not store messages permanently, does not scale across multiple servers, and does not support advanced messaging features.

Without a broker

Suppose you have three users.

Alice
Bob
Charlie

Alice sends

Hello

Now your controller would have to know

Who is online?
Who joined Room 1?
Send to Bob.
Send to Charlie.

You'd have to write all that yourself.

With a Simple Broker

The broker maintains a table like this:

Destination              Subscribers
--------------------------------------------
/topic/room/1           Alice, Bob, Charlie
/topic/room/2           David, John
/topic/news             Alice, John

When a message arrives

Destination:
/topic/room/1

Body:
Hello

The broker automatically delivers it to

Alice

Bob

Charlie
Where do you configure it?
@Configuration
@EnableWebSocketMessageBroker
public class WebSocketConfig
        implements WebSocketMessageBrokerConfigurer {

    @Override
    public void configureMessageBroker(
            MessageBrokerRegistry registry) {

        registry.enableSimpleBroker("/topic");

        registry.setApplicationDestinationPrefixes("/app");
    }
}

This line

registry.enableSimpleBroker("/topic");

starts Spring's in-memory broker.

What does /topic mean?

Suppose the server sends

messagingTemplate.convertAndSend(
        "/topic/room/1",
        message
);

Because

enableSimpleBroker("/topic")

exists,

Spring says

"This destination belongs to the broker."

The broker then forwards it to all subscribers.

What is /app?

This is not handled by the broker.

Suppose client sends

SEND

destination:
/app/chat

Spring routes it to

@MessageMapping("/chat")

So the flow becomes

Client

↓

SEND /app/chat

↓

Controller

↓

convertAndSend("/topic/room/1")

↓

Simple Broker

↓

Subscribers

Notice the difference.

/app

means

"Go to my controller."

/topic

means

"Go to the broker."

Complete example
Client sends
SEND
destination:/app/chat

Hello

Spring calls

@MessageMapping("/chat")
public void send(ChatMessage msg){

    messagingTemplate.convertAndSend(
            "/topic/room/1",
            msg
    );

}

Now broker receives

Destination:
/topic/room/1

Body:
Hello

Broker checks

Who subscribed?

Alice

Bob

Charlie

Broker sends

Hello

↓

Alice

↓

Bob

↓

Charlie
Is it like RabbitMQ?

Very similar in purpose, but much simpler.

RabbitMQ

Separate server
Persistent queues
Durable messages
Acknowledgements
Routing exchanges
Cluster support

Simple Broker

Runs inside Spring Boot
Memory only
No persistence
No clustering
Very fast to start
When should you use Simple Broker?

Good for

Chat applications
Notifications
Learning
College projects
Small to medium applications